value.value: A specialized, columnar, mucus secreting epithelial cell shaped like a flask or goblet. A narrow basal end contains the nucleus while the apical end is swollen by the accumulation of mucus laden secretory granules.  Short microvilli project from the apical plasma membrane.
A large, oval stomach epithelial cell with a central nucleus; source of gastric acid. Secretes HCl.
A cell of an endocrine gland, ductless glands that secrete substances which are released directly into the circulation and which influence metabolism and other body functions.
An endocrine cell that is located in the epithelium of the gastrointestinal tract or in the pancreas.
A neuron that is capable of some hormone secretion in response to neuronal signals.

The neurosecretory cell is neither an ordinary neuron nor an endocrine cell, but a combination of both. Its neuronal features resemble those of ordinary neurons concerning both structure and function. The production of a visible secretory material marks the neurosecretory neuron as a gland cell, and the fact that extractable cellular products act in the manner of hormones places it in the realm of endocrine elements. 

The modern definition of neurosecretion has evolved to include the release of any neuronal secretory product from a neuron.

A cell that stores epinephrine secretory vesicles. During times of stress, the nervous system signals the vesicles to secrete their hormonal content. Their name derives from their ability to stain a brownish color with chromic salts. Characteristically, they are located in the adrenal medulla and paraganglia of the sympathetic nervous system.
Any secretory cell that is capable of some peptide hormone secretion.
Any secretory cell that is capable of some insulin secretion.
A cell that secretes insulin and is located towards the center of the islets of Langerhans.

definition.value: Pancreatic beta cells are also reportedly CD284-positive. Upon activation, they upregulate their CD14 expression.

value.value: A cell that secretes glucagon.
A type of enteocrine cell found in the periphery of the islets of Langerhans that secretes glucagon.
Any secretory cell that is capable of some somatostatin secretion.
A D cell located in the pancreas. Peripherally placed within the islets like type A cells; contains somatostatin.
Any secretory cell that is capable of some steroid hormone secretion.
A progesterone secreting cell in the corpus luteum. The large luteal cells develop from the granulosa cells. The small luteal cells develop from the theca cells.
Any secretory cell that is capable of some testosterone secretion.
A Leydig cell is a testosterone-secreting cell in the interstitial area, between the seminiferous tubules, in the testis.

definition.value: Note that the Amphibian Anatomy Ontology (AA) has a class 'leydig cells' but this is unrelated

value.value: Any secretory cell that is capable of some progesterone secretion.

The main structural component of the liver. They are specialized epithelial cells that are organized into interconnected plates called lobules. Majority of cell population of liver, polygonal in shape, arranged in plates or trabeculae between sinusoids; may have single nucleus or binucleated.

definition.value: Hepatocytes are reportedly MHC Class I-positive and MHC Class II-positive.

value.value: A cell whose primary function is to shorten.
Contractile cells resembling smooth muscle cells that are present in glands, notably the mammary gland, and aid in secretion. This cell has long weaving dendritic processes containing myofilament.
A mature contractile cell, commonly known as a myocyte. This cell has as part of its cytoplasm myofibrils organized in various patterns.
A somatic cell located in skeletal muscle.
A muscle cell that develops tension more slowly than a fast-twitch fiber.
A muscle cell that can develop high tension rapidly. It is usually innervated by a single alpha neuron.
A non-striated, elongated, spindle-shaped cell found lining the digestive tract, uterus, and blood vessels. They develop from specialized myoblasts (smooth muscle myoblast).

definition.value: A cell that is capable of detection of a stimulus involved in sensory perception.

value.value: The peripheral receptor for pain. Includes receptors which are sensitive to painful mechanical stimuli, extreme heat or cold, and chemical stimuli. All mammalian nociceptors are free nerve endings.

definition.value: Editor note: request detection of stimulus involved in sensory perception of pain; add develops_from relationship

value.value: A cell specialized to transduce mechanical stimuli and relay that information centrally in the nervous system.
Any neuron that is capable of some detection of mechanical stimulus involved in sensory perception of touch.

A mechanoreceptor cell of the auditory or vestibular system that is sensitive to auditory stimuli. The accessory sensory structures are arranged so that appropriate stimuli cause movement of the hair-like projections (stereocilia and kinocilia) which relay the information centrally in the nervous system.

definition.value: In mammals these cells are located in the organ of Corti.

value.value: A cell specialized to detect chemical substances and relay that information centrally in the nervous system. Chemoreceptors may monitor external stimuli, as in taste and olfaction, or internal stimuli, such as the concentrations of oxygen and carbon dioxide in the blood.
Any neuron that is capable of some detection of chemical stimulus involved in sensory perception of smell.
A specialized cell involved in gustatory sensory perception.
A cell specialized to detect and transduce light.
A cell whose function is determined by the generation or the reception of an electric signal.
A cell within an epithelial cell sheet whose main function is to act as an internal or external covering for a tissue or an organism.

definition.value: A cell located in the synovial joint.

value.value: A cell whose primary function is to prevent the transport of stuff across compartments.

A supporting cell projecting inward from the basement membrane of seminiferous tubules. They surround and nourish the developing male germ cells and secrete androgen binding protein. Their tight junctions with the spermatogonia and spermatocytes provide a blood-testis barrier.
A neuroglial cell of the peripheral nervous system which forms the insulating myelin sheaths of peripheral axons.
A cell that moves by its own activities.
A cell of the outer of the three germ layers of the embryo.
A cell of the middle germ layer of the embryo.
A cell of the inner of the three germ layers of the embryo.
A cell that lacks a nucleus.
A cell with a single nucleus.
Any cell that has characteristic some binucleate.
A cell with more than one nucleus.
